    {
      "id": "RkueDlTeMRKUm0Nl1LeSG",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1265.6800002119385,
      "y": 76570.43402440583,
      "width": 154,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "btN",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1875855886,
      "version": 7,
      "versionNonce": 1309328914,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1777689612051,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "ANN Approach: ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "ANN Approach: ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "JkFWtFCHh17MxxbztCh5B",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1310.3783412587452,
      "y": 76615.09930183228,
      "width": 968,
      "height": 175,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "btO",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1616505234,
      "version": 8,
      "versionNonce": 1640843474,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1777689693906,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Approximate nearest neighbor (ANN) is an algorithm that finds a data \npoint in a data set that's very close to the given query point,\n but not necessarily the absolute closest one.\n\n\nIt sacrifices a tiny amount of accuracy (it might return 9 of the top 10, plus the 11th)\n for a massive gain in speed (often orders of magnitude faster).",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Approximate nearest neighbor (ANN) is an algorithm that finds a data \npoint in a data set that's very close to the given query point,\n but not necessarily the absolute closest one.\n\n\nIt sacrifices a tiny amount of accuracy (it might return 9 of the top 10, plus the 11th)\n for a massive gain in speed (often orders of magnitude faster).",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "R7r4OaxXdSiuo3o8x6Wde",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1305.3453234865651,
      "y": 76916.62115121301,
      "width": 847,
      "height": 600,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "#ffc9c9",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "btP",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 477744718,
      "version": 9,
      "versionNonce": 1980881742,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1777690154159,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Clustering /Inverted File Index - IVF\nPhase 1: Indexing (The one-time setup)\nFind the \"Centers\": The database first looks at all of your million vectors \nand uses an algorithm (like k-means clustering) to find, let's say, \n100 \"center points\" or centroids. Each centroid is itself a vector that \nrepresents the average of a region in your data. Think of these as the \nsigns for the sections in our library: \"Fiction,\" \"Science,\" etc.\n\nAssign to Clusters: The database then goes through every single one of \nyour million vectors and figures out which of the 100 centroids it's closest \nto. It then puts a \"pointer\" to that vector into a list for that centroid.\n\n\nSearching (When you make a query)\nNow you come with your query vector for \"light blue summer shirt.\"\nFind the Closest Section(s): The database does NOT compare your \nquery to all one million vectors. Instead, it just compares it to the \n100 centroids. This is super fast. It finds that your query is closest \nto, say, \"Centroid #42\" (the \"men's casual shirts\" section).\n\nSearch Only Within That Section: Now, the database knows your best \nmatches are probably in the list for Centroid #42.\nSo it only searches through the 10,000 vectors in that one cluster.\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Clustering /Inverted File Index - IVF\nPhase 1: Indexing (The one-time setup)\nFind the \"Centers\": The database first looks at all of your million vectors \nand uses an algorithm (like k-means clustering) to find, let's say, \n100 \"center points\" or centroids. Each centroid is itself a vector that \nrepresents the average of a region in your data. Think of these as the \nsigns for the sections in our library: \"Fiction,\" \"Science,\" etc.\n\nAssign to Clusters: The database then goes through every single one of \nyour million vectors and figures out which of the 100 centroids it's closest \nto. It then puts a \"pointer\" to that vector into a list for that centroid.\n\n\nSearching (When you make a query)\nNow you come with your query vector for \"light blue summer shirt.\"\nFind the Closest Section(s): The database does NOT compare your \nquery to all one million vectors. Instead, it just compares it to the \n100 centroids. This is super fast. It finds that your query is closest \nto, say, \"Centroid #42\" (the \"men's casual shirts\" section).\n\nSearch Only Within That Section: Now, the database knows your best \nmatches are probably in the list for Centroid #42.\nSo it only searches through the 10,000 vectors in that one cluster.\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
