    {
      "id": "y65ZQbAilJ6ULkMKB0759",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1266.0657424499473,
      "y": 80380.82891512635,
      "width": 726,
      "height": 25,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "byA",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 902977874,
      "version": 41,
      "versionNonce": 364865106,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1777693094659,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Fouth Method -> The Compression Method (Product Quantization - PQ)",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Fouth Method -> The Compression Method (Product Quantization - PQ)",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "OxrjUuKxTOeKU6A_M4rVD",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1306.5870461194036,
      "y": 80409.86416982143,
      "width": 924,
      "height": 275,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "byB",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 604845582,
      "version": 9,
      "versionNonce": 1843783054,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1777693875871,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "A single vector using 1536 dimensions of 32-bit floating-point numbers \ntakes up 1536 * 4 bytes = 6,144 bytes. If you have a billion vectors,\n that's 6.1 Terabytes of RAM! That's incredibly expensive.\n\n\nIt chops the big vector into smaller segments. For example, \na 16-dimension vector could be chopped into 4 segments of 4 dimensions each.\n[d1, d2, ..., d16] -> [chunk1], [chunk2], ..., [chunk4]\n\nV = [1.1, 2.3, 0.9, 3.4, 8.8, 7.6, 9.1, 6.5, 4.2, 5.5, 3.9, 5.1, 9.9, 8.1, 7.7, 9.3]\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "A single vector using 1536 dimensions of 32-bit floating-point numbers \ntakes up 1536 * 4 bytes = 6,144 bytes. If you have a billion vectors,\n that's 6.1 Terabytes of RAM! That's incredibly expensive.\n\n\nIt chops the big vector into smaller segments. For example, \na 16-dimension vector could be chopped into 4 segments of 4 dimensions each.\n[d1, d2, ..., d16] -> [chunk1], [chunk2], ..., [chunk4]\n\nV = [1.1, 2.3, 0.9, 3.4, 8.8, 7.6, 9.1, 6.5, 4.2, 5.5, 3.9, 5.1, 9.9, 8.1, 7.7, 9.3]\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "wXjmBfe_IS46j06RBBe9U",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1349.8636514889586,
      "y": 80698.38466891336,
      "width": 880,
      "height": 600,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "byC",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 920148494,
      "version": 56,
      "versionNonce": 1010793486,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1777694007359,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Step A: Split V into chunks.\nv_chunk1 = [1.1, 2.3, 0.9, 3.4] -> [10]\nv_chunk2 = [8.8, 7.6, 9.1, 6.5] -> [23]\nv_chunk3 = [4.2, 5.5, 3.9, 5.1] ->[123]\nv_chunk4 = [9.9, 8.1, 7.7, 9.3] -> [16]\n\n\nStep B: Create the Codebooks (k cluster/centroid)\nChunk 1 (dims 1-4): We take all the first chunks and look at Codebook 1.\nChunk 2 (dims 5-8): We do the same for the second chunks and look at Codebook 2.\nChunk 3 (dims 9-12): This gives us Codebook 3.\nChunk 4 (dims 13-16): This gives us Codebook 4\n\ncodeBook1 look like this\n\n0 : [1.2,3.6,4.7,2.1]\n1 : [1.1,3.2,4.5,2.8]\n2 : [2.2,3.6,5.7,1.1]\n3 : [1.1,2.4,1.0,3.3]\n.\n.\n.\n255 : [4.2,3.6,1.7,2.1]\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Step A: Split V into chunks.\nv_chunk1 = [1.1, 2.3, 0.9, 3.4] -> [10]\nv_chunk2 = [8.8, 7.6, 9.1, 6.5] -> [23]\nv_chunk3 = [4.2, 5.5, 3.9, 5.1] ->[123]\nv_chunk4 = [9.9, 8.1, 7.7, 9.3] -> [16]\n\n\nStep B: Create the Codebooks (k cluster/centroid)\nChunk 1 (dims 1-4): We take all the first chunks and look at Codebook 1.\nChunk 2 (dims 5-8): We do the same for the second chunks and look at Codebook 2.\nChunk 3 (dims 9-12): This gives us Codebook 3.\nChunk 4 (dims 13-16): This gives us Codebook 4\n\ncodeBook1 look like this\n\n0 : [1.2,3.6,4.7,2.1]\n1 : [1.1,3.2,4.5,2.8]\n2 : [2.2,3.6,5.7,1.1]\n3 : [1.1,2.4,1.0,3.3]\n.\n.\n.\n255 : [4.2,3.6,1.7,2.1]\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "8AsxIfo151Sn5HTxwuMBQ",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1952.7750957690287,
